{"id":"1409.2014","submitter":"Yong Zhang","authors":"Norbert Mauser, Hans Peter Stimming and Yong Zhang","title":"A novel nonlocal potential solver based on nonuniform FFT for efficient\n  simulation of the Davey-Stewartson equations","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.comp-ph math.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We propose an efficient and accurate solver for the nonlocal potential in the\nDavey-Stewartson equation using nonuniform FFT (NUFFT). A discontinuity in the\nFourier transform of the nonlocal potential causes accuracy locking if the\npotential is solved by standard FFT with periodic boundary conditions on a\ntruncated domain. Using the fact that the discontinuity disappears in polar\ncoordinates, we reformulate the potential integral and split it into high and\nlow frequency parts. The high frequency part can be approximated by the\nstandard FFT method, while the low frequency part is evaluated with a high\norder Gauss quadrature accelerated by nonuniform FFT. The NUFFT solver has\n$O(N\\log N)$ complexity, where $N$ is the total number of discretization\npoints, and achieves higher accuracy than standard FFT solver, which makes it a\ngood alternative in simulation. Extensive numerical results show the efficiency\nand accuracy of the proposed method.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 6 Sep 2014 13:53:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 3 Oct 2014 09:07:12 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 28 Sep 2016 18:02:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-09-29"}
